[[File:Yabu-jinja, entrance.jpg|thumb|250px|{{center|Precinct entrance}}]]
'''Yabu Shrine''' (やぶじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Ichiba, {{ill|lt=Yabu|Q869014|WD=Q869014|1=Yabu, Hyōgo}}, {{ill|lt=Hyogo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}. It is the {{ill|lt=Tajima Province|Q1053727|WD=Q1053727|1=Tajima Province}} {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=third-ranking provincial shrine (sannomiya)|1=Ichinomiya}}, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} (2 myōjin-taisha seats and 3 small-shrine seats), and under the former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} system it was a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}.

It is popularly called "Yabu no Myojin-san" and is known as a deity of agriculture. Ichiba in Yabu has long been a center of cattle markets for {{ill|lt=Tajima cattle|Q13417172|WD=Q13417172|1=Tajima cattle}}, and auctions are still held at nearby Ōyabu.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The five currently enshrined seats are:
* {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}}
* {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōanamuji-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}
* {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|WD=Q3275687|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona}}
* {{ill|lt=Tanba Michinushi no Kimi|UNKNOWN|lt=Tanba Michinushi-no-Mikoto}}
* Funahotari-no-Mikoto - descendant of Tanba Michinushi-no-Mikoto and ancestor of the provincial rulers of Tajima
In ''Tajima-kō'', a regional record compiled in the Edo period, it is described that once the upper shrine on Mt. Yadaka enshrined Ōanamuji-no-Mikoto, the middle shrine on the mid-slope enshrined Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto and Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto, and the lower shrine at the present site enshrined Tanba Michinushi-no-Mikoto. ''{{ill|lt=Tokusen Jinmeichō|Q11571092|WD=Q11571092|1=Tokusen Jinmyōchō}}'' treats four seats other than Ōanamuji as uncertain. ''Yabu Gunshi'' (1928) gives the upper shrine deities as {{ill|lt=Ukemochi|Q2280323|WD=Q2280323|1=Ukemochi}} and {{ill|WD=Q10881556|lt=Isotakeru|Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|1=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto}}, the middle shrine as Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto, and the lower shrine as Tanba Michinushi-no-Mikoto and Funahotari-no-Mikoto<ref name="bunken1">''Gods of Japan (7) San'in'', p.331</ref>.

=== History ===
Tradition says the shrine was founded in the 30th year of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|WD=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}, and it is already named together with {{ill|lt=Izushi Shrine|Q3156511|WD=Q3156511|1=Izushi Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Awaga Shrine|Q11604651|WD=Q11604651|1=Awaga Shrine}} in the ''Tajima no Kuni Zeiseichō'' of {{ill|lt=Tenpyō|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} 9 ({{ill|lt=737|Q23583|WD=Q23583|1=AD 737}}).

For divine court rank, it received junior fifth rank lower in {{ill|lt=Jōwa (Japan)|Q1075605|WD=Q1075605|lt=Jōwa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} 12 (845) (''{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihon Kōki|Q1041301|WD=Q1041301|1=Shoku Nihon Kōki}}''), rose to senior fifth rank lower in Jōgan 11 (869), and to senior fifth rank upper in Jōgan 16 (874) (''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}''). The ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' records "Yabufuza Shrine, five seats (two myōjin-tai and three small seats)"<ref name="bunken1" />.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, Suisenzan Fugen-ji served as the attached temple.

In {{ill|lt=1814|Q6943|WD=Q6943|1=1814}} (Bunka 11), {{ill|lt=Ino Tadataka|Q1240937|WD=Q1240937|1=Inō Tadataka}} visited during his {{ill|lt=surveying|Q816425|WD=Q816425|1=Surveying}} expedition.

